Set and frozen-set.

A set is an unordered collection of unique, hashable elements. Membership is constant time.

The set operators map directly to set algebra. Pipe for union — in either. Ampersand for intersection — in both. Minus for difference — in left, not in right. Caret for symmetric difference — in one or the other, not both. Less-equal and less-than for subset and proper subset — every element of left in right. Greater-equal and greater-than for the reverse.

Frozen-set is the immutable variant — same operations, no mutation. Required when you need a set as a dict key or as an element of another set.

In code, picture warm as red, orange, yellow. Cool as blue, green, violet. Primary as red, blue, yellow. Warm pipe cool is the union. Warm ampersand primary is the intersection — red, yellow. Warm minus primary is orange. Warm caret primary is the symmetric difference, orange plus blue. Subset checks — warm less-equal warm pipe cool is true. The set red less-equal warm is true. Mutating methods — add, discard which is no-error if absent, remove which is key-error if absent. Frozen-set — hashable, can be a set element or dict key. A container of two frozen-sets works.
